Design a quantum key distribution (QKD) protocol using entangled photon pairs. Describe how Alice and Bob can use these pairs to generate a shared secret key, ensuring that any eavesdropping attempt by an adversary will be detectable.

\begin{align*}
&\text{Alice generates two entangled photon pairs, } (\phi_A^0, \phi_A^1), (\phi_B^0, \phi_B^1). \\
&\text{Alice sends } \phi_A^0 \text{ to Bob and keeps } \phi_A^1 \text{ for herself.} \\
&\text{Bob measures } \phi_B^0 \text{ in a random basis, either } Z \text{ or } X. \\
&\text{Alice measures } \phi_A^1 \text{ in the same basis as Bob's measurement.} \\
&\text{If Bob measures } \phi_B^0 \text{ in the } Z \text{ basis and finds } \phi_A^1 \text{ in the } Z \text{ basis, he records a 0. If he measures } \phi_B^0 \text{ in the } X \text{ basis and finds } \phi_A^1 \text{ in the } X \text{ basis, he records a 1.} \\
&\text{If Bob detects any deviation from this, it indicates eavesdropping.} \\
&\text{The shared secret key is generated by comparing the results of Alice's and Bob's measurements.}
\end{align*}

